<Page
    x:Class="Salami.HistoryPage"
    xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
    xmlns:local="using:Salami"
    xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008"
    xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006"
    mc:Ignorable="d">

    <ScrollViewer>
        <StackPanel Spacing="24" Padding="24">
            <!-- Header -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="12">
                <TextBlock Text="History of Salami" 
                          FontSize="42" 
                          FontWeight="Bold"/>
                <TextBlock Text="A journey through centuries of meat curing excellence" 
                          FontSize="18" 
                          Opacity="0.8"/>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Ancient Origins -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="Ancient Origins" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"/>
                </Border>
                
                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="12">
                        <TextBlock FontSize="18" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            Salami has roots stretching back to ancient times. The practice of preserving 
                            meat through curing, drying, and fermentation was essential for survival before 
                            refrigeration. Ancient Roman and Greek texts mention cured sausages, and the 
                            word "salami" itself derives from the Italian "salare," meaning "to salt."
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock FontSize="18" TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            The earliest forms of salami were likely created by Mediterranean peoples who 
                            needed to preserve meat during long journeys and harsh winters.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Medieval Era -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="Medieval Era (500-1500 AD)" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"/>
                </Border>
                
                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="12">
                        <TextBlock FontSize="18" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            During the Middle Ages, salami production became more refined throughout 
                            Southern Europe, particularly in Italy. Each region developed its own unique 
                            recipes, spice blends, and curing techniques that are still celebrated today.
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock FontSize="18" TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            Monasteries and wealthy estates perfected the art of salami making, with monks 
                            documenting recipes and techniques. These became closely guarded secrets passed 
                            down through generations of butchers and sausage makers.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Renaissance & Modern Era -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="Renaissance to Modern Era" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"/>
                </Border>
                
                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="12">
                        <TextBlock FontSize="18" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            By the Renaissance period, Italian salami makers had achieved master status. 
                            Cities like Genoa, Milan, and Naples became famous for their distinctive styles. 
                            Trade routes spread these delicacies across Europe and eventually to the New World.
                        </TextBlock>
                        <TextBlock FontSize="18" TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                            The 19th and 20th centuries saw Italian immigrants bringing their salami-making 
                            traditions to America, Australia, and other parts of the world, where they 
                            adapted recipes to local tastes while maintaining traditional methods.
                        </TextBlock>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Traditional Methods -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiPink}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="Traditional Curing Methods" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="{StaticResource SalamiRed}"/>
                </Border>
                
                <Grid>
                    <Grid.ColumnDefinitions>
                        <ColumnDefinition Width="*"/>
                        <ColumnDefinition Width="*"/>
                    </Grid.ColumnDefinitions>

                    <Border Grid.Column="0"
                           Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                           CornerRadius="8" Padding="20" Margin="0,0,8,0">
                        <StackPanel Spacing="12">
                            <TextBlock Text="Fermentation" FontSize="24" FontWeight="SemiBold"/>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Natural bacteria convert sugars into lactic acid, lowering pH and 
                                preventing harmful bacteria growth while developing complex flavors.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>
                    </Border>

                    <Border Grid.Column="1"
                           Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                           CornerRadius="8" Padding="20" Margin="8,0,0,0">
                        <StackPanel Spacing="12">
                            <TextBlock Text="Air-Drying" FontSize="24" FontWeight="SemiBold"/>
                            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Opacity="0.8">
                                Salamis are hung in temperature and humidity-controlled rooms for 
                                weeks or months, allowing moisture to evaporate and flavors to intensify.
                            </TextBlock>
                        </StackPanel>
                    </Border>
                </Grid>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Cultural Impact -->
            <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                <Border Background="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                       CornerRadius="8" 
                       Padding="20">
                    <TextBlock Text="Cultural Significance" 
                              FontSize="32" 
                              FontWeight="Bold"
                              Foreground="White"/>
                </Border>
                
                <Border Background="{ThemeResource CardBackgroundFillColorDefaultBrush}"
                       CornerRadius="8" Padding="24">
                    <StackPanel Spacing="16">
                        <TextBlock FontSize="18" TextWrapping="Wrap">
                            Salami is more than just food—it's a cultural icon. In Italy, each region 
                            takes pride in its local salami varieties, often protected by PDO 
                            (Protected Designation of Origin) status.
                        </TextBlock>
                        <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                            <TextBlock Text="• Celebrated in annual festivals across Europe" FontSize="16"/>
                            <TextBlock Text="• Central to charcuterie traditions" FontSize="16"/>
                            <TextBlock Text="• Symbol of artisanal craftsmanship" FontSize="16"/>
                            <TextBlock Text="• Brings families together at meals" FontSize="16"/>
                            <TextBlock Text="• Represents regional pride and identity" FontSize="16"/>
                        </StackPanel>
                    </StackPanel>
                </Border>
            </StackPanel>

            <!-- Quote -->
            <Border BorderBrush="{StaticResource SalamiRed}" 
                   BorderThickness="3" 
                   CornerRadius="8" 
                   Padding="32">
                <StackPanel Spacing="12" HorizontalAlignment="Center">
                    <TextBlock Text="&quot;In every slice of salami lies centuries of tradition, skill, and passion&quot;" 
                              FontSize="24" 
                              FontStyle="Italic"
                              TextAlignment="Center"
                              TextWrapping="Wrap"
                              MaxWidth="600"/>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>
        </StackPanel>
    </ScrollViewer>
</Page>
